Process called "create_svm" that takes 
    kernel as Optional[String]
    and C as Optional[Float]
    and gamma as Optional[String]
    returns SupportVectorMachine:

    Note: Create Support Vector Machine classifier
    Return SupportVectorMachine with:
        kernel as kernel or "rbf"
        C as C or 1.0
        gamma as gamma or "scale"
        support_vectors as empty list
        support_vector_labels as empty list
        alpha as empty list
        bias as 0.0
        is_fitted as false

Process called "fit_svm" that takes 
    model as SupportVectorMachine
    and X_train as df.DataFrame
    and y_train as df.DataFrame
    returns SupportVectorMachine:

    Note: Train SVM model using simplified SMO algorithm
    Try:
        Note: This is a simplified implementation
        Note: Real SVM would use Sequential Minimal Optimization (SMO)
        
        Let X_matrix be convert_dataframe_to_matrix with df as X_train
        Let y_vector be df.get_dataframe_column_values with 
            df as y_train 
            and column as y_train.columns[0]
        
        Let n_samples be length of X_matrix
        
        Note: Initialize alpha values
        Let alpha_values be empty list
        For i from 0 to n_samples minus 1:
            Add 0.0 to alpha_values
        
        Note: Simplified training - select all points as support vectors
        Let support_vectors be X_matrix
        Let support_labels be y_vector
        
        Return SupportVectorMachine with:
            kernel as model.kernel
            C as model.C
            gamma as model.gamma
            support_vectors as support_vectors
            support_vector_labels as support_labels
            alpha as alpha_values
            bias as 0.0
            is_fitted as true
    
    Catch error:
        Return model

